The way I'm doing it in my current story is that nominally herbivore types can eat meat, but they don't prefer it or seek it out. Same goes for carnivores.

Most of the rest could be spoilers, and since it's not really plot relevant, there's little reason for me to show the full depth of autism on the part of food that are.

Anonymous Wed 01 Jun 2022 03:50:03 No.48173677 Report
Quoted By: >>48173778 >>48173847 >>48173904
>>48172966
Any how much tech is left over?
Say a full-out TNW kills 3 of 9 billion from the actual strikes or direct radiation poisoning. Now let's say that half of the remainder dies of later fallout, contamination, or other secondary effects.
We're down to 3 billion, and they have an unstable food supply, a sharp drop in medical care, infrastructure damage, and much else.
Basically, you'd have a massive die-off due to limited resources. A smart enemy would have hit anything strategic, and those would be cities and areas with all your capacity.

Go look at a map of the US with 300 largest cities + 100 military bases, then overlay a decent 50 mile radius on each. Then look up the effects of Chernobyl on farming in Europe.
The 2-3 generation population change would be massive.

It my setting, I had to do a lot of thinking on why a plague didn't lead to a nuclear situation. 50% dead was enough for me.
